    <title>Finally, HP is adding AI to its printers</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="An image showing an HP DeskJet printer" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/NJTwLoGPlIiKlrfug6WgKnZkg-g=/0x50:900x650/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73610312/hp_printer_deskjet_edit.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: HP&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="zuJYZO"&gt;HP has a groundbreaking announcement. No, it’s not making it easier to use &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/3/11/23635168/hp-printer-update-brick-third-party-ink-dynamic-security"&gt;cheaper, third-party ink&lt;/a&gt;, nor does it have a solution for frequent paper jams and irritating software issues. &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.hp.com%2Fus-en%2Fnewsroom%2Fpress-releases%2F2024%2Fhp-print-ai.html&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F9%2F25%2F24254129%2Fhp-print-ai-beta-launch-printers" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;It’s bringing AI to printers&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="K9uJa2"&gt;The new HP Print AI experience is rolling out today in an “exclusive” beta and comes with a Perfect Output feature that’s supposed to clean up printouts of webpages. HP says it will automatically detect unwanted content like ads or weird formatting, allowing it to print just the “desired text and images.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="eBs8V3"&gt;&lt;div data-anthem-component="imageslider:12435908"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p id="YA0Exk"&gt;It’s also supposed to optimize printouts of spreadsheets by keeping charts and tables on a single page, instead of splitting them up. But that’s not all — HP says you can use “conversational prompts” with Print AI to turn...&lt;/p&gt;
